Duck Typing is a concept in programming languages where an object is considered to be of a certain type if it has a certain set of methods or properties, even if it's not explicitly defined as that type. In TypeScript, you can use duck typing to check if an object has certain properties or methods, without having to declare the object as a specific type.

For example, in TypeScript, you can declare a variable as a "duck" type, and then check if it has certain properties or methods:
```
interface Duck {
  quack(): void;
  fly(): void;
}

let myDuck: Duck = {
  quack: () => { console.log("Quack"); },
  fly: () => { console.log("Fly"); }
};

// This will not throw an error because myDuck has the quack and fly methods
myDuck.quack();
myDuck.fly();
```
